### #2 — `ClientTerrainSorter::PrimitiveNode` (clientTerrain)

**Why it ranks high:** **1647 and 2664 are exact multiples of 9** — the only writer whose batch unit is 9 verts/patch.

| Item | Location |
|------|----------|
| **Format (36 B with 1 UV set)** | ```77:88:src/engine/client/library/clientTerrain/src/shared/appearance/ClientTerrainSorter.cpp``` |
| **Lock** | ```298:298:src/engine/client/library/clientTerrain/src/shared/appearance/ClientTerrainSorter.cpp``` |
| **Write loop** | ```308:344``` — 9 verts per terrain primitive from `positionList/normalList/colorList` |
| **Space** | Positions copied raw from `primitive->getPositionList()`; **O2W set to terrain** @ ```367:367``` — not CPU world-bake, but coords are planet-scale (~3000+) |
| **Counts** | Batch accumulates `numberOfVertices += 9` per queued patch @ ```614:614```; max batch ~256KB / 36 ≈ 7281 verts |

**Tail stale mechanism:** Unlikely — loop always writes exactly `9 × primitiveList->size()` which equals `numberOfVertices`. No partial-subbatch transform pointer. Would need a batch accounting bug (not visible in current code).

**Mismatch with NPC spike:** Terrain draws aren’t tied to a single creature’s bounding volume; centroid at NPC world pos could be coincidental (terrain patches near player).

